        <poem xml:id="p-55">
            <title>Neighbor</title>
            
                <stanza>
                    <lb num="1"/>Down home
                    <lb num="2"/>he sets on a stoop
                    <lb num="3"/>and watches the sun go by.
                    <lb num="4"/>In Harlem
                    <lb num="5"/>when his work is done
                    <lb num="6"/>he sets in a bar with a beer.
                    <lb num="7"/>He looks taller than he is
                    <lb num="8"/>and younger than he ain't.
                    <lb num="9"/>He looks darker than he is, too.
                    <lb num="10"/>And he's smarter than he looks,
                </stanza>
                <stanza>
                    <lb num="11"/>
                        <format wordType="italics" margin="ind1">He ain't smart.</format>
                    
                    <lb num="12"/>
                        <format wordType="italics" margin="ind1">That cat's a fool.</format>
                    
                </stanza>
                <stanza>
                    <lb num="13"/>Now he ain't neither.
                    <lb num="14"/>He's a good man,
                    <lb num="15"/>except he talks too much.
                    <lb num="16"/>In fact, he's a great cat.
                    <lb num="17"/>But when he drinks,
                    <lb num="18"/>he drinks fast.
                </stanza>
                <stanza>
                    <lb num="19"/>
                        <format wordType="italics" margin="ind1">Sometimes</format>
                    
